":"Cork 9, Cork, County Cork, Ierland"},"en":{"12 August 1593–1615":"12 August 1593–1615","1585–1631":"1585–1631","1586–1620":"1586–1620","1588–Male":"1588–Deceased","1590–Female":"1590–Deceased","1593–1615":"1593–1615","1585–1643":"1585–1643","1615–1712":"1615–1712","1615–1691":"1615–1691","1560–1592":"1560–1592","1565–1640":"1565–1640","1560":"1560","1593":"1593","1592":"1592","1691":"1691","1590":"1590","12 August 1593":"12 August 1593","1712":"1712","1643":"1643","1588":"1588","1565":"1565","1620":"1620","1631":"1631","1586":"1586","1640":"1640","1585":"1585","about 1583":"about 1583","1615":"1615","1603":"1603","England":"England","Cork, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Cork 9, Cork, County Cork, Ireland","Cork, Cork, Ireland":"Cork 9, Cork, County Cork, Ireland","Cork 9, Cork, County Cork, Ireland":"Cork 9, Cork, County Cork, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Broughton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places in all parts of England called Broughton. The first element is variously Old English <i>brōc</i> ‘brook’, <i>burg</i> ‘fortress’, or <i>beorg</i> ‘hill, mound’; the second is in all cases Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Braughton","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Broughton  ."]},{"name":"Brought","meanings":["English: shortened form of   Broughton  .","Americanized form of German   Braucht  ."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."],"variants":[{"name":"Anni","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]},{"name":"\"Helen\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["vernacular form of the name (Greek <i>Hēlēnē</i>) borne in classical legend by a famous beauty, wife of Menelaus, whose seizure by the Trojan prince Paris sparked off the Trojan War. Her name is of uncertain origin; it may be connected with a word meaning ‘ray’ or ‘sunbeam’ compare Greek <i>hēlios</i> ‘sun’. It has sometimes been taken as connected with the Greek word meaning ‘Greek’, <i>Hellēn</i>, but this is doubtful. In the early Christian period the name was borne by the mother of the Emperor Constantine, who is now usually known by the Latin version of her name, <i>Helena</i>. She is credited with having found the True Cross in Jerusalem. She was born in about  248 , probably in Bithynia. However, in medieval England it was believed that she had been born in Britain, which greatly increased the popularity of the name there."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1355925,"age":9,"year":"1603","julianDay":2306544,"description":"Accession of James I. Surrender of Hugh O'Neill. Enforcement of English Law in Ireland.","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"When Anne \"Helen\" Broughton was born on 12 August 1593, in Cork 9, Cork, County Cork, Ireland, her father, Edward Broughton, was 33 and her mother, Anne Dixwell, was 28. She had at least 2 daughters with Sir John Borodell \"Knight\". She died in 1615, in her hometown, at the age of 22."},"et":{"12 August 1593–1615":"12. august 1593–1615","1585–1631":"1585–1631","1586–1620":"1586–1620","1588–Male":"1588–Surnud","1590–Female":"1590–Surnud","1593–1615":"1593–1615","1585–1643":"1585–1643","1615–1712":"1615–1712","1615–1691":"1615–1691","1560–1592":"1560–1592","1565–1640":"1565–1640","1560":"1560","1593":"1593","1592":"1592","1691":"1691","1590":"1590","12 August 1593":"12. august 1593","1712":"1712","1643":"1643","1588":"1588","1565":"1565","1620":"1620","1631":"1631","1586":"1586","1640":"1640","1585":"1585","about 1583":"umbes 1583","1615":"1615","1603":"1603","England":"England","Cork, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Cork 9, Cork, County Cork, Iirimaa","Cork, Cork, Ireland":"Cork 9, Cork, County Cork, Iirimaa","Cork 9, Cork, Co